{
  "_comment": "THE RG-D RUN LISTS, and the only place they live in this project. Transcribed verbatim from clas-framework's clas12/include/clas12/Runs.hpp, which is where the collaboration's lists are recorded. The note (sec:runs, tab:runs) says of the originals: 'These lists are not applied by any binary' -- they documented the run ranges but did not constitute the production selection. THIS FILE EXISTS TO END THAT. pi0.farm reads it and REFUSES any input file whose run is not in the requested (polarity, target) list, so the run selection is a checked property of the production rather than a property of whichever directory someone happened to scan. Counts verified against tab:runs: outbending LD2 135, CxC 112, CuSn 268; inbending LD2 24, CxC 8, CuSn 27. The three outbending lists are pairwise disjoint (verified) and total 515 distinct runs spanning 18419-19131, confirming each run carried a single target.",
  "_schema_version": 1,
  "_generated": "2026-07-17, from clas-framework clas12/include/clas12/Runs.hpp",
  "_target_vs_runlist_comment": "RUN LISTS ARE KEYED BY RUN-LIST NAME, NOT BY ANALYSIS TARGET. There are three run lists (LD2, CxC, CuSn) but FOUR analysis targets (LD2, CxC, Cu, Sn). Cu and Sn are two foils in one assembly exposed in the SAME CuSn runs and separated offline by vertex (note sec:vertex); stageA_skim --target Cu and --target Sn read the same input files and differ only in the electron vz window. So: target Cu -> run list CuSn, target Sn -> run list CuSn. pi0.farm.TARGET_TO_RUNLIST encodes exactly this and nothing else.",
  "_polarity_comment": "OUTBENDING ONLY IS THE PRODUCTION. The inbending lists are recorded here for completeness and as the cross-check the analysis lacks (note sec:outlook: 'Run the inbending dataset -- both for statistics and as the detector-systematic cross-check the analysis currently lacks entirely'). THE TRAP THIS FILE DEFUSES: inbending and outbending runs live in the SAME /mss directory tree per target -- LD2 inbending is 18305-18336 and LD2 outbending starts at 18419 -- so a naive recursive scan of /mss/clas12/rg-d/production/pass1/recon/LD2/dst/recon/ silently pulls inbending files into an 'outbending' production, mixing torus polarities in one dataset. Nothing downstream would notice: the polarity is not in the slim schema. Filtering by these lists is the only thing standing between a directory scan and that.",
